  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- These typically mirror federal provisions and provide additional legal frameworks\n\n3. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. also participates in international anti-money laundering efforts through organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n\nKey components of these statutes generally include:\n- Criminalizing the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Providing mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nPenalties can be significant, often involving substantial monetary fines and potential prison sentences depending on the specific circumstances and amount involved.",
